Mount Carmel College of Nursing
September 10 at 12:07 PM ·

September 10 is World Suicide Prevention Day. Every 40 seconds, someone in the world takes their own life. All races, ages and income levels are at risk for considering or attempting suicide. If you need someone to talk to, or are worried about a family member or friend, contact the Lifeline Network, available 24/7 across the U.S at 1-800- 273-8255. #WorldSuicidePreventionDay

post_text:
Meet the Staff:

“When asked about my favorite moments while working at this school, a specific conversation came to mind. While working on a video project where students focused on “One Word,” I asked a young man about the one word he was going to choose to describe our school. He told me that after growing up in a violent school environment, his word was “peace.” That is powerful.”

Mr. Clark (Math Teacher, Microsoft Specialist, Print & Media Extraordinaire)

That is something I’ll never forget.” 🥳

post_text:
Meet the staff: Hannah Tiell, Intervention Specialist

“My favorite part of teaching at FPHS is the relational connectivity I get to have with my students. Every day when they walk in, we get to have conversations about the fun thing they did over the weekend or their favorite hobby. I love that I get to build relationships with my students instead of just being their teacher. One of my favorite parts of each day is celebrating milestones with stickers and candy! 🍭🍬” ￼￼￼￼

post_text: We have been so fortunate to partner with community health workers David and Aakifah from Mount Carmel for the past two years. They have been so helpful to our students on their weekly visits. Now they’ve gone a step further and helped one of our former students become a community health worker as well. They intend to work with another student throughout this process this year as well! We are so proud of Millie and can’t wait to see how she helps those in our community!

Meet the Franklinton Prep Staff: Mrs. Harris, Healthcare Instruction

“I have a passion￼ for helping people achieve their dreams and more importantly, helping people survive! I love that I have the opportunity to use my skills that I learned as a nurse with educating future phlebotomist and the endless opportunities that are available in the healthcare field. I hope to inspire students who want to enter into the nursing industry and enlarge their ￼￼￼￼￼￼￼benefits of services to others in this challenging yet rewarding way. I look forward to empowering and supporting students of Franklinton Prep in any way I can. I also look forward to changed lives… One student at a time.”

post_text:
Meet the staff! Math teacher, Mrs. Riesterer

“Math is a tough subject, and finishing up multiple credits to prepare for graduation is no joke! Still, Mr. Clark and I are committed to helping every student power through and the fun moments along the way keep us going when the work gets hard. To help students, I love preparing little charts, notes and videos for reference. Even better is when we get to work through things together, discussing tips and tricks for solving different types of problems. Despite whatever this pandemic may throw at us during this next year, we're excited to find creative ways to continue earning credits while building the relationships with students that make all of our hard work worth it. We've missed you all but I look forward to getting back in the classroom for another fun year together!”

post_text:
Meet The Staff: Next up is Assistant Director Ms. Eisel!

“This will be my 14th year in education. Prior to becoming Assistant Director at Franklinton Prep, I worked the previous two years under Mr. Mintos at Central High. Before that I was an English teacher for 11 years. In May, I graduated with my masters in educational leadership from Ohio Dominican University.

Last school year I loved watching all of the phlebotomy students learn real-life job skills! It was fun to see them start out so nervous, but then walk away as confident adults ready to join the workforce! I can’t wait for this year’s round of new phlebotomy students!”

post_text:
Meet the Staff: first up, Mr. Mintos- Director

“I get the most enjoyment seeing the faces of graduates as they line up right before the ceremony begins. It is a pensive look as the student prepares for their life to shift. In their faces I can see every spirited conversation we had, every time they wanted to give up, every time their heart was broken. To see them standing proud about their journey through every negative obstacle to get to that celebratory moment, it reminds me that everyone’s story is worth telling. I love seeing that range of emotions shine through.”
